## What is the problem with Java Null Pointer Exception?
A java.lang.NullPointerException occurs when an attempt is made to dereference the null object. This means that as it is not possible to access a class’s members because that class is not instantiated, this exception will be thrown. It is one of the most commonly reported runtime errors in Java. It will be shown if you try to access a null object (in most cases the result of a mistake like: this.myClassThatIsNull.myMethod()). If it appears very often in your code, it means you are using null too much (you should not use null at all).
You have to check if the “object” you are using is not null
Example 1:
    if (mObject != null) {
        return mObject.someMethod();
    } else {
    	Throw some exception...
    }

#### Why a Java Null Pointer Exception occurs?
The java.lang.NullPointerException is the most common exception in Java. It occurs when your code attempts to access the members of an object through a reference that is null (i.e has never been instantiated), and the JVM detects that the program is referring to an object that is not there, i.e has not been instantiated.
The error is thrown by the Java virtual machine (JVM) when it encounters a piece that is supposed to be referring to an object, but does not refer to anything. Such problems are very common in coding where the programmer incorrectly sets an initial object to NULL without first ensuring that an object or a block of memory is allocated before it is assigned a value.
The Null Pointer Exception is also known as the NullPointerException. The reason for the Null Pointer Exception to occur is because an object is pointing to nothing and not to a valid object. Because we are assuming that the Java virtual machine is a safe environment in which to execute code, the null pointer exception is a major security threat. It implies the possibility of a malicious program or a program that is out of control intentionally causing the null reference Exception. If the programmer does not handle it properly, the program will crash, and this will lead to data loss, a corrupt database, and/or damage to physical hardware. There is an old saying that programmers are lazy, but that does not apply to you.
Now, the question is, why is the Null Pointer Exception thrown? Because the code tries to use something that doesn't have a value/point to something. It is the default value that Java sets whenever you try to assign a variable a null value. In other words, what it means is that trying to point to something that does not exist, such as a null value, will cause the error. When there is a new program that runs for a while, it works perfectly, but over time the code in it starts to misbehave, and it stops working.
A Null Pointer Exception in Java is a type of unchecked exception. This means that this error does not happen often even though it is a critical error, although it may occur. This exception is mainly caused by a programmer's mistake to set an object to NULL (i.e it is instantiated without first checking).

#### How to solve Java Null Pointer Exception?
In Java, the simplest way to resolve the NullPointerException error is to check if the object has a value by using an if statement — or in other words if it is not null. The object is not set to null before using the object; therefore the java virtual machine will be able to throw a NullPointerException. The problem here is that not all cases will be detected like this, and also the compiler won't report any errors — the exceptions are runtime errors, so it will not be detectable by the compiler.
The way to solve this error is to check on all the objects if it was instantiated by using if (object !=null) before using the object. A common way to solve this problem is to declare the variable as a final variable.
In other words, an instance variable cannot be assigned a null value unless it is already initialized to an object reference; therefore, to avoid Null-Pointer Exception errors, the final variables have to be initialized. So, if you try to assign a null value to a reference variable final, you will be able to run the application; however, it will not be able to find the address of your newly instantiated object, and the result will be a Null-Pointer Exception error.

